  <caaml:metaData>
    <caaml:comment>Relatively stable snowpack conditions are observed on moderately steep slopes with a N/NE aspect. &#13;
&#13;
The entire mountain is severely windblown and the surface snow is hard, uneven, crusty, and icy in spots.&#13;
The location where the snowpit was dug was one of the very few spots on the entire slope with some windblown powder on top.&#13;
&#13;
The layer of potential concern starts at around 35 cm deep (at this location at least - will likely be shallower in most other places). There is some sugary snow present in it and the layer below as well.&#13;
However, despite this, its surface is not too slippery, with 2 consequtive compression test performed, and on average there is some breakup of the layer above it around CT27 and a smooth, Q2 slide on its surface at the very end on CT30.&#13;
&#13;
The layer below this one also contains some sugary snow crystals in spots.&#13;
&#13;
No spontaneous avalanche activity is anywhere in the region. Given the forecast the trend will likely continue over the next week on similar slopes.</caaml:comment>
